 overs people paint them out to be. Through jealousy and misunderstanding do stories get told and passed around like idle gossip from pick up groups to guilds. After a while, it gets to be this image that people expect of the said "uber" guild. /shrug Be that as it may, not everyone is a saint; we all have our flaws (and bad apples in the barrel). <P>A lot of us have been playing this game for nearly three years. I have only been playing this game for two. Sure friends are a joy to have in your guild. Friends also don't have to wear the same guild tag in order to stay friends. (Which is why sometimes I wish my friends lists were larger so i could keep tabs on some of em hehehe). <P>After a while there is only so much you can do in this game. You can help other people obtain items, levels, etc. but sooner or later you're going to want to do something for *you*. It's that darned humanity factor. For a lot of people it's seeing high level encounters, it's seeing new zones that you were previously unable to see (NToV comes to mind), it's experiencing what being part of a team of people doing things with strats you never thought would work, being part of a large machine that is working towards a common goal of defeating an imposing and awesome force. <P>You have to look and see what type of guild you are. Are you a raiding guild? Are you a guild that plans workshops on the best methods of going about certain tradeskills? For every person there is a different directive and motivation about why they chose their classes and how they play this game the way they do. That's what makes this game such a success because it has a little bit of everything for everyone. <P>Your goal and/or task is going to have to be attracting the types of players you would like. If you say that you are a "friend-type guild that raids"... you're going to have to raid. And gauge it according to the responses you get. That is how you will succeed. <P>And Bolgor, you said you targeted 60 warriors first. Warriors and melees are VERY gear/weapons oriented people. They want to constantly improve what they have (well, doesn't everyone to a certain extent?). By joining a "uber" guild they will have effectively taken the next step to achieve that goal. Keep that in mind when they politely decline your invitation to join your guild. <P>Okay I think I'm done rambling now :P<P>*edit* Okay I just re-read this and I'm coming across a little harshly. =\ Not the way I intended it, so please don't read too much into it.<P>Spawrhawk Wormwood<BR>59 Templar of Fennin Ro<p>[This message has been edited by Spawrhawk (edited 01-28-2002).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">NightGod</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Well Spawrhawk-I gotta agree with you. When we lost our first couple people to the server uber guild, there was "a great wailing and gnashing of teeth", so to speak.<P>Then we all pretty much realized that if yer not happy playing the game how you are now, why the hell are you still paying your $10/mo to be here?<P>So now, when we lose someone, they get a "good luck, enjoy the ride, do what makes you happy".<P>And everyone is alot happier. Oh, and we've gotten to the point where we can start doing some of those uber mobs, even without the people we lost. Last two server Woushi kills were by my guild, Talendor down, Ixiblat is basically a pick-up raid, triggered Trak, Chardok Queen (WOW-that's a nasty pull), Lodizal, HoT, we're bored of the planes (as a guild, some sickos like me still like to go-hehe-pick up planar raids are good for bumping the blood pressure), VS/Phinny are a nessicary evil etc etc. Just trying to say, just because you lose that "OMG key member", you will survive, you will move on, you will grow. Tell them good luck, enjoy the game, and be sure to say hi.<P>Cause in the end, its about playing the game for fun and seeing your friends do the same, no matter what guild tag is above t